<font color="#FF0000">MR. BEAN MORE HONORABLE THEN</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov  9 22:45:32 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
MR. BEAN IS MORE HONORABLE THEN SPATZ<br><br>
Get off it spatz, <br>
Even Mr. Bean is more honorable then you.<br>
Your dead like that dog in the wire, but even a corpse involuntary sits up sometimes.<br><br>
No one believes you anymore. You have a very deceiving mouth that spews nothing but death, hate and destruction. There is nothing reliable in what you have to say. You have clothed yourself in the colors of the enemy’s flag. Embraced their courage while dishonoring your own countrymen. <br><br>
What ever you touch you bring to ruin. You flatter with your tongue but your heart is havvah (Hebrew for perverse). You seek to inflame and place a wedge between those that oppose your hypocrisy, lawlessness that amoral convictions. <br><br>
Even your smooth and sweet words are full of bitter wine, the venom of serpents. You hide mockery under your tongue, desire evil, relish its sickness and fondle its dilapidated stench.<br>
 <br>
You covet what you believe are the riches of the world, but the real wealth of fine gold that has been tried in the furnace of life, the honor and glory of courage found in battle you will never inherit, you will never know. And so throughout your life you have no choice but to lust after the honor given men of war. Men who have shed blood in their nations battles. You desire their power, strength and courage but that virtue will never be yours. That type of valor your fragile bowels would never endure, your own fears have forever robbed you of its honor. <br><br>
No, spatz, you will never know the taste nor the true wealth of a soldier. And while you will forever crave its glory and honor it will always be beyond your reach.  Even Israel saw through your cowardly heart and would not accept you among those who would fight against the odds. <br>
So little spatz continue to attack and try to distort the truth, seek those of your kind who will justify your sense of amorality as your forefathers did before you.<br><br>
I feel sorry for you should your sons ever read what honorable men have written about you.  <br>

<p><code>-- Shooting the dead dog in the wire for practice   (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


